# Wine Platform Middleware — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is a TypeScript monorepo (Turborepo) that provides a shared middleware layer
connecting wine commerce platforms (Commerce7, OrderPort, WithWine) to Framer-based
storefronts. Consumer projects are thin, config-only Vercel deployments.

## Monorepo Structure
- packages/core        — shared types, interfaces, utilities, and the defineConfig() factory
- packages/adapter-commerce7  — Commerce7-specific API adapter implementing core interfaces
- packages/adapter-orderport  — OrderPort-specific API adapter implementing core interfaces
- packages/adapter-withwine   — WithWine-specific API adapter implementing core interfaces
- packages/framer      — Framer integration: origin/token/CORS access control + product serializer
- apps/*               — consumer Vercel deployments (one per client, config-only)

## Core Architectural Rules

### Package Boundaries
- packages/core has ZERO platform-specific code. No Commerce7/OrderPort/WithWine imports.
- Each packages/adapter-* imports from packages/core only. Never from another adapter.
- packages/framer imports from packages/core only (for the Product type). No platform/adapter
  imports, and it stays framework-agnostic (no next/@vercel/node deps).
- Consumer apps import the adapter that matches their platform + core for defineConfig()
  + (optionally) framer for Framer access control and serialization.
- No circular dependencies across any packages.

### defineConfig() Pattern
- Every consumer app configures via a Zod-validated defineConfig() exported from packages/core.
- defineConfig() must validate at build time and throw descriptive errors on bad config.
- Config schema lives in packages/core/src/config.schema.ts — never in adapters or apps.
- Adapters receive a resolved, validated config object — they never call defineConfig() themselves.

### Adapter Interface Contract
- All adapters must implement the PlatformAdapter interface from packages/core.
- Interface covers: getProducts(), getProduct(), createOrder(), getCart(), updateCart(),
  getMember(), getClub(), getAvailability().
- Adapters are responsible for mapping platform-native responses to core shared types.
- Throw typed errors from packages/core — never raw Error objects or platform-specific errors.

### TypeScript Rules
- Strict mode on across all packages. No "any" types — use "unknown" and narrow.
- All public API surfaces must have explicit return types.
- Shared types live in packages/core/src/types/. Adapters never define their own public types.
- Use Zod for all runtime validation (config, API responses from external platforms).

### Build (tsup)
- Each package builds independently via tsup.
- Output: CommonJS + ESM dual build. Types emitted via tsc.
- Entry point for each package: src/index.ts.
- Do not bundle node_modules. Mark all cross-package deps as external.

### Vercel / Consumer Apps
- apps/* are config-only. No business logic lives in app directories.
- Each app exports a config file (e.g., withwine.config.ts) calling defineConfig().
- API routes in apps proxy through the adapter — they do not call platform APIs directly.
- Environment variables follow the pattern: PLATFORM_API_KEY, PLATFORM_STORE_ID, etc.
- Framer-facing routes use packages/framer for the origin allowlist + token gate + CORS;
  do not re-implement that security per app.
- WithWine consumers are full Next.js (Pages Router) apps — its auth SDK requires a Next.js
  server. Use apps/template-withwine as the canonical template. Platforms without that
  requirement can use the same template, or bare @vercel/node functions.

### Distribution
- Packages are published to GitHub Packages (@decant/core, etc.).
- Consumer repos reference packages via package.json with exact versions.
- Dependabot is configured on consumer repos to track package updates.

### Error Handling
- Define all error types in packages/core/src/errors.ts.
- Errors must carry: code (string enum), message, platform (optional), httpStatus (optional).
- Adapters catch platform-specific errors and rethrow as core typed errors.
- API routes return consistent JSON error shapes — never expose raw platform error messages.

### Naming Conventions
- Files: kebab-case (product-adapter.ts, not productAdapter.ts).
- Exported classes/interfaces: PascalCase.
- Exported functions/constants: camelCase.
- Zod schemas: suffixed with Schema (e.g., ConfigSchema, ProductSchema).
- Types: prefixed with nothing — just the noun (Product, Order, Cart, Member).

### Testing
- Unit tests live alongside source files: product-adapter.test.ts next to product-adapter.ts.
- Integration tests live in packages/adapter-*/tests/integration/.
- Mock platform API responses in tests — never hit live APIs in test runs.
- Use vitest across all packages.
